Fix ZeroDivisionError in benchmarking code.

Due to some sloppy coding on my part, if a particular benchmark
ran too fast in JSON (most likely on Windows, which has a lower
time.time() resolution), we would divide by zero when computing
the speedup.

This patch rewrites things to avoid that, and makes the output
a bit more detailed.

This fixes https://github.com/dpranke/pyjson5/issues/42.

commit.message: Fix indent in nested list/dict
Bump version to v0.9.1, clean up README a bit.

Fix stray trailing comma when dumping an object with an invalid key.

json5.dumps({"foo": 1, (1, 2): 2}, skip_keys=true) would incorrectly print
a trailing comma if the `(1, 2)` item was found as the second item in
the list.

This was reported in https://github.com/dpranke/pyjson5/issues/33. This
only showed up in Python3 and not Python2, because of differences in the
ordering of the dictionary keys. This change also rewrites the test for
this to use OrderedDicts() to address that, and adds a test for a dict
with only invalid keys as well, for comprehensiveness.
Bump version to v0.9.0.
Note bug fixes #30, #29 in the README, fix other typos.

GH #30: Fix bug in handling circular references.

This change addresses https://github.com/dpranke/pyjson5/issues/30,
where objects with other objects as values weren't tracked correctly,
leading the implementation to incorrectly think there were
circular data structures in some cases.

GH #29: Fix quoting for object key that start with a reserved word.

This addresses https://github.com/dpranke/pyjson5/issues/29, where
an the object key `newbie` in `{newbie: true}` was being incorrectly
quoted since newbie starts with the reserved word `new`.

GH#27: Remove README from package data.

This change addresses https://github.com/dpranke/pyjson5/issues/27,
where README.md was being included in the source distribution (and in
a bad location, to boot); it is not necessary to include it, since
the contents are in the longdesc field of the package.

Add allow_duplicate_keys=False to dump()/dumps().

Commit 46ca46 fixed an issue with dump()/dumps() but introduced
the possibility for the routine to generate ill-formed JSON.

This change adds an optional `allow_duplicate_keys` keyword parameter
to the routines. By default the value is True, and duplicates will
be allowed, to match the behavior of json.dump() and json.dumps().
However, if you pass `allow_duplicate_keys=False`, any duplicates that
result from the string conversions will produce a ValueError exception
instead.

GH #32: Allow for non-string keys in dicts.

This fixes https://github.com/dpranke/pyjson5/issues/32, where
json5.dumps({1: "foo"}) didn't work correctly. It will now match
the `json` module's output by casting 1 to a string, i.e., producing
'{"1": "foo"}'.

Note that this means that by default, you may produce ill-formed JSON
in some caes, with duplicate keys if you mix numbers and strings.

For example, {1: "foo", "1": "bar"} -> '{"1": "foo", "1": "bar"}'.
This matches the `json` module's behavior, for better or worse.
bump version to 0.9-dev
bump version to v0.8.5

Fix bad error reporting on partial matches.

This patch addresses an error reported in
https://github.com/dpranke/pyjson5/issues/26, where calling
`json.loads('[ ,]') would report an error on column 4, not column 3.

The reason for this had to do with the way the optional whitespace (sp*)
rule was coded in the grammar, and a bug in the underlying parser generator
(glop), where if you had a rule like (a ?())* and you matched a and not b,
the errposition wouldn't be properly rolled back before the conditional
expression. That bug was fixed in glop v0.6.2; this CL regenerates the
JSON5 parser with that version of the parser generator, and then adds
json5-specific tests to check for the correct position reporting.

Include README.md, LICENSE in the source distribution.

This addresses https://github.com/dpranke/pyjson5/issues/25
and adds //README.md and //LICENSE to the sdist files.

Fix dumps([], indent=2).

This addresses https://github.com/dpranke/pyjson5/issues/26:
`json5.dumps([], indent=2)` incorrectly returned '[\n  ,\n]',
when it should've returned '[]' (and the did the same thing for
objects).
